The anwer to your question is **No**. You can&#39;t loop in HTML. HTML is a descriptive language, it describes the elements of your page. 

To enable itself with programming capabilities, HTML defines the `&lt;script&gt;` tag. Browsers support it and are able to interpret and execute the code it contains. For historic reasons, the code is written in **javascript** language. 

In your case, you need to change the contents of the page programmatically. To do so, you don&#39;t change the HTML, but manipulate the **DOM**, the internal representation of the page in the browser, once the page has finished loading. The javascript support in browsers has standardized some methods to access the DOM and manipulate (insert, delete, change) the DOM contents.

You first must create a `&lt;script defer&gt;` tag inside your page `&lt;head&gt;`. The `defer` attribute specifies that you want your code to run after the complete page has been loaded and the DOM has been constructed.

    &lt;script defer&gt;
    &lt;/script&gt;

Then you need to (1) find your `&lt;form&gt;` in the page (2) copy it five times (3) giving all of them (including the original) unique IDs and (4) inserting the copies into the DOM after the original form, before the next element that follows the original form.

```    
let originalForm=document.querySelector(&quot;form&quot;);   //(1)
let insertionPoint=form.nextSibling;  //(4)
originalForm.id=&quot;form-1&quot;;  //(3)
for (let i=2;i&lt;=6;i++) {  //(2)
  let copied = originalForm.cloneNode(true); //(2)
  copied.id=&#39;form-&#39;+i; //(3)
  originalForm.parentNode.insertBefore(copied, insertionPoint); //(4)
}
```

